    "narrative_summary": "The BRCA2 c.1141G>A (p.Asp381Asn) missense change is listed in the ENIGMA multifactorial likelihood analysis of BRCA1/2 variants and is the subject of clinical classification efforts. The variant has been reported in public databases and appears in supplementary tables of several genomic studies, but no disease\u2011specific case reports are described in the extracted evidence.\nClinical evidence from the ENIGMA quantitative analysis indicates that the combined likelihood ratio for c.1141G>A does not reach the thresholds for a definitive benign (<0.5) or pathogenic (>2) classification, although the authors note evidence favoring a benign interpretation. ClinVar entries for this allele include both \"likely benign\" and \"uncertain significance\" designations, reflecting conflicting interpretations of pathogenicity [PMC6772163].\nPopulation data from the same ENIGMA supplement show that the variant is observed at a low allele frequency (\u22650.0001 and <0.01) with the highest minor allele frequency reported in Latino individuals, and it is classified as a missense_variant. No functional assay results or computational predictive scores are provided in the extracted material.\nOverall, the available evidence suggests that BRCA2 c.1141G>A is a rare missense variant with limited and conflicting clinical interpretation. The multifactorial likelihood framework leans toward a benign classification, but the lack of decisive likelihood ratios, functional data, and consistent clinical consensus means that the variant remains of uncertain significance, with a tendency toward likely benign status.",
    "structured_summary": {
        "overall_pathogenicity": "benign",
        "pathogenicity_counts": {
            "supports pathogenicity": 0,
            "uncertain": 0,
            "supports benignity": 1
        },
        "conflicting_evidence": false
    },
